http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/Timber-smuggling-foiled-in-Bandipur/article13994069.ece

Forest guards opened fire on a gang of timber smugglers in Maliyur range of Bandipur Reserve Forest area on Sunday evening, injured one of them.The forest guards, who spotted a gang of around eight smugglers in the forests, were forced to open fire when the smugglers attacked them with sickles and saws. One of the smugglers, who suffered a bullet injury in the leg, is undergoing treatment at K.R. Hospital in Mysuru.Maliyur range Assistant Conservator of Forests (ACF) G. Venkatesh told The Hindu that the smugglers had felled teak trees in the forests and had kept six logs ready to be ferried as head loads when the Forest Department personnel reached the spot as part of their routine combing operations.“Each log had been cut to weigh around 40 to 50 kg. When they saw the Forest Department personnel, they abandoned the logs and fled from the spot. When our personnel started chasing them, they turned around and attacked our guards with sickles and saws”, G. Venkatesh said.The Forest Department personnel fired at their legs from a distance. While the rest of them managed to escape, Channanayaka, a resident of Basapura in H.D. Kote taluk of Mysuru district, suffered a bullet injury. He was initially taken to the government hospital in H.D. Kote, but was later shifted to K.R. Hospital in Mysuru, where he is undergoing treatment.The Forest Department has also seized the abandoned teakwood logs. Officials said residents of various villages including Basapura were notorious for smuggling teak from the forests.